<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Community Housing Cymru_x000b_</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Community Housing Cymru</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Community Housing Cymru Group (CHC Group)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is the representative body for housing associations and community mutuals in Wales, which are all not-for profit organisations. Our members provide over 153,000 homes and related housing services across Wales. In 2011/12, our members directly employed 7,5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">00 people and spent over £850m in the Welsh economy.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Our members work closely with local government, third sector organisations and the Welsh Government to provide a range of services in communities across Wales.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Our objectives are to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Be the leading voi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce of the social housing sector. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Promote the social housing sector in Wales.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Promote the relief of financial hardship through the sector's provision of low cost social housing. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Provide services, education, training, information, advice and support to mem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bers.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Encourage and facilitate the provision, construction, improvement and management of low cost social housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by housing associations in Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2010, CHC formed a group structure with Care &amp; Repair Cymru and CREW Regeneration Wales in order to j</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ointly champion not-for-profit housing, care and regeneration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">General Comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the membership body for housing associations in Wal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es, Community Housing Cymru has repeatedly detailed its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> concerns about the impact of many of the current welfare reforms,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> both on housing associations and their tenants in Wales. Wales has been disproportionately hit by many of the changes, in particular the social sector size criteria – the so called ‘bedroom tax’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Yet, housing associations in Wales have been at the forefr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ont of looking for innovative solutions of dealing with the changes – working within the devolution settlement to lobby Welsh Government for further support, and working with Community Housing Cymru on the ‘Your Benefits Are Changing’ information campaign,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which has been working to support thousands of people through the changes to welfare.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To date, the Your Benefits Are Changing adviser</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s have given telephone and face-to-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">face advice to over 4,000 members of the public, identifying in excess of £450,000 of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">budget savings through unclaimed benefits, debt relief schemes such as the Welsh Water Customer Assistance Fund and schemes such as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Warm Home Discount. This campaign</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has worked across all sectors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and in partnership with a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">number of local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and voluntary organisations including Shelter Cymru and Citizens Advice Cymru, as well as all of CHC’s members.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our response will look to focus on the impact the changes to the welfare system will have on housing associations in Wales, as well as their t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enants, and how support for vulnerable claimants can be improved.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Social Sector Size Criteria</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have a number of conc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erns about this policy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and have detailed these in dialogue with DWP, the Welsh Affairs Committee and Welsh Government since the introdu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ction of the Welfare Reform Act at the beginning of this Parliament.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In evidence to the Welsh Affairs Select Committee in 2012, members of Community Housing Cymru made it clear that “</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we do not necessarily agree with the criteria that suggest that [tenants</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> deemed to be under-occupying] have extra bedrooms. Those of us who have been doing some new build have been building to a pattern book. Often we have been doing the pattern book with a furniture lay-out that shows that you can get only one single bed into</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a bedroom. Now people who occupy those houses are being told that they have to put in bunk beds.”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These concerns rema</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the early stages of this po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">licy, the indications are that (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as warned by Community Housing Cymru and a hug</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e number of other or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ganisations) there simply is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n’t the volume of smaller properties available for tenants deemed to be under-occupying to downsize into. Figures released by housing associations in the Gwent area after just four months of the policy revealed nearly £200,000 w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">orth of arrears from tenants who had not previously fallen behind on their rent.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Members of Community Housing Cymru have highlighted that these problems are even more acute in rural areas, where downsizing options are even furt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">her limited than in urban </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he nearest available appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sized property would require a tenant to move to a different community many miles away, with little or no access to vital support networks. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cymdeithas Tai Eryri, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a North W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ales based housing association,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reported</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to Community Housing Cymru that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> arrears problems caused by this policy have increased due to seasonal pressures on income</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, such as the need to buy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more food in the summer months when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children don’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t receive free school meals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Further seasonal increases in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the cost of living, such as heating costs during the winter, are likely to have a similar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffect.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Housing associations in Wales have been proact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ive in dealing with this change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> along with the work done through the Your Benefits Are Changing campaign, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have come up with a number of innovative ways of helping tenants to adapt to these changes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RCT Homes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a Large Scale Voluntary Transfer organisation based in the Rhondda C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ynon Taf local authority area, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have used two tenant service based methods which ref</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lect their area of operation in terms of demand and occupation, and complement other initiatives being run by the organisation, on financial inclusion and sustainability. The first method used – Smart Move – aims to give financial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assistance to tenants aff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ected by the under-occupancy charge, who wish to downsize their accommodation where the home they would be vacating is in an area of high demand. Running alongside this, the second ini</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tiative is a rent relief fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aimed at assisting people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have little </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or no chance of being rehoused due to various circumstances, but make a commitment to volunteering, training or work opportunities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cartrefi Cymunedol Gwynedd has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> invested heavily in mitig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ating the impact of this policy. They have employed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> four rent advisors to get the message to tenants and supp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ort them to pay rent, and added</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a further £30,000 to their Rent Recovery budget to cover additional costs e.g. processing direct debit payments, and other administrative costs. This is occurring wid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ely across the RSL sector in Wales, and the investment required to keep rent arrears low will only increase upon the introduction of further welfare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reforms. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While the UK Government has increased the budget for Discretionary Housing Payments (DHPs) to al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">leviate problems caused by this policy, we have a number of concerns around DHPs, the budget and the way in which some local authorities are administering the funds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Discretionary Housing Payments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While we have welcomed the increased budget for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Discretionary Housing Payments over the coming years, we do have some concerns in this area. As outlined by CHC members in evidence to the Welsh Affairs Select Committee in 2012, the discretionary nature of these payments causes long term uncertainty for t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hose who receive them. CHC feel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the only substitute for this increased DHP budget, which has been put in place to deal with the social sector size criteria, would be an increase in the scope of exemptions from this policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Community Housing Cymru al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so has concerns about the way some local authorities are administering the fund, specifically in relation to people receiving disability benefits who are affected by the social sector size criteria. We are concerned that the simple nature of income/expendi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ture tests on the DHP applications often means that those receiving Disability Living Allowance or Personal Independence Payments are expected to divert some of this income – intended for mobility or care – to cover their housing benefit shortfall. Due to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these concerns, we have recently co-signed a letter to all Local Authority Heads of Housing in Wales requesting that local authorities disregard income from disability-related benefits when assessing DHPs, since it is intended to be used to meet the extra </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">costs of disability.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Additional money for the DHP budget in rural areas was welcomed by many in the sector, but brought with it further concerns. Community Housing Cymru</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> members on Ynys Môn (Anglesey)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> felt that a simple population density calculation to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">determine whether an area would get further funding was not effective. One member felt that the issue of suitable housing stock levels, coupled with rurality and proximity to support or family networks were an even greater barrier in both Welsh and English</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> speaking areas in rural North West Wales and that the allocation of extra DHP had not recognised this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Localised Council Tax Support</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The implications of localised council tax support and the reduced budget with which it was devolved to Wales has yet to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be felt fully. Welsh Government plugged the funding gap for the first year of the scheme in Wales, meaning that all those who previously received Council Tax Benefit (CTB) continued to do so. However, with continually reducing revenue budgets, it would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">understandable if Welsh Government could not continue to cover this shortfall.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The devolution of Council Tax support to Wales also highlighted a wider point around intra-government relations between DWP and Welsh Government, and the politicisation of soci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al security policy decisions. In our response to the Silk Commission on Devolution in Wales</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, we highlighted that a lack of communication between Whitehall and Cardiff Bay had far-reaching implications in this instance. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Your Benefits Are Changing hel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pline – set up by Community Housing Cymru and run by our Big Lottery funded money advice team – seeks to advise people on the changes made to the welfare system, and deal with some of the most vulnerable and financially excluded people in society. A lack o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f clarity over the future of council tax support meant that up until an announcement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by Welsh Government on January 17th 2013, nearly 80% of callers to the Your Benefits Are Changing phone line were advised that they would no longer receive some o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r all of their Council Tax Benefit. The policy announcement followed a number of inter-governmental debates over the funding, regulations etc., with the proposed cut to council tax set to be introduced less than three months later, on April 1st. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We urge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both DWP and Welsh Government to give more clarity over such policy decisions and their implications in future, and would be keen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">see improved communications to ensure that devolved governments can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clearly communicate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their intentions, especially where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the devolution settlement or localisation of support offers opportunity for policy divergence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Household benefit cap</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The impact of the benefit cap in Wales is a relatively small compared to many of the other welfare reforms, but not in any way insignificant. Community Housing Cymru believes this policy to be an ineffective way to bring down the welfare bill. The increasi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng spend on housing benefit is down to a lack </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of supply of affordable housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d increasing private rents. F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or a significant decrease in the welfare bill to be realised, these issues must be tackled first.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Direct Payment of Housing Costs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DWP’s Demonstra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion Projects have given both housing providers and the DWP an opportunity to understand how payment of housing costs directly to the claimant wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll work under Universal Credit. As</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stated in the Learning and Payment figures from May 2013, experiences in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Welsh demonstration project in Torfaen have shown that arrears amongst tenants on direct payments are significantly higher than amongst the general tenant population.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The project has also shown that under direct payment, rent collection will become a far</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> mor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e resource intensive exercise, often for a lower yield, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and staffing levels will have to be increased significantly.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In a recent survey, one member of Community Housing Cymru indicated that they were considering running their own small demonstration p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roject of direct payments to gauge the amount of support and advice that will be required once Universal Credit is introduced. However, this will require a large scale consultation with tenants to understand exactly what support and payment services etc. w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ill be required to run this pilot.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Support for vulnerable claimants</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Supporting vulnerable claimants through the introduction of Universal Credit and beyond is both complex and time and resource intensive, and the DWP must recognise this both in defining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> vulnerability and through the provision of support services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A report from the National Housing Federation – our sister organisation in England – found that 29% of claimants are likely to require intensive long-term support to help them manage their fina</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nces effectively.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As stated in our response to the Local Support Services Framework</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, we have grave concerns that the mismanagement of transition to Universal Credit will have huge implications for landlords who do not have the resources to provide the le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vel of support many tenants will require.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Welsh housing associations already provide a huge number of support services for their tenants, including money and financial, advocacy and welfare benefits advice in recognition of the high number of vulnerable h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ouseholds. Many provide in-house advice for their tenants, while others have service agreements with external advice providers. Feedback from members is that they are working to increase the support services they provide as Universal Credit and other welfa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re reforms come into effect.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Supported Exempt Accommodation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Community Housing Cymru welcomes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work currently being undertaken by DWP on supported exempt accommodation to ensure that all schemes intended to fall outside Universal Credit do so. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Universal Credit</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">During consultation with members on this call for evidence, a number of concerns were registered around the whole Universal Credit project and the process of implementing it.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Members indicated that there had been a lack of information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from DWP, and how the Department intends to work with RSLs to support tenants on their claimant journey. Many RSLs felt that their rent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or welfare officers were in a good position to work with DWP to identify those tenants who would cope with the changes a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd those who would require various levels of support, but that there had been a lack of engagement from DWP in discussing these issues, and DWP are missing out on vital local information that could add value and effectiveness to the switch to Universal Cre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dit.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Members have also called for reassurance that they will know which tenants are claiming Universal Credit. One member suggested that a real-time user interface, linking to the DWP’s, was required to allow them to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">apply efficiently for alternate paymen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t methods as the rent arrears increase – and enable the decision for alternate payments to be made and implemented quickly before RSLs start rent recovery procedures against tenant who need support.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cartrefi Cymunedol Gwynedd highlighted the work they are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> doing with local Citizens Advice Bureaux, the local authority and DWP to dev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elop local support services. However, they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> felt </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the lack of information from DWP wasn’t allowing them to prepare these services properly, and gave them very little knowledge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of what exactly they are building the support services for.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">27 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Measuring the Economic Impact of Welsh Housing Associations, November 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmwelaf/uc1050-iii/uc105001.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmwelaf/uc1050-iii/uc105001.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/10621068.Gwent_tenants_owe___190_000_after_housing_benefit_changes/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.southwalesargus.co</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">.uk/news/10621068.Gwent_tenants_owe___190_000_after_housing_benefit_changes/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://chcymru.org.uk/resources1/documents/key-issues/Commission_on_Devolution_in_Wales_-_Second_call_for_evidence_-_CHC_Group_response__February_2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http:/</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">/chcymru.org.uk/resources1/documents/key-issues/Commission_on_Devolution_in_Wales_-_Second_call_for_evidence_-_CHC_Group_response__February_2013.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Optimising welfare reform outcomes for social tenants understanding the financial management issues fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r different tenant groups, Policis</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://chcymru.org.uk/resources1/documents/key-issues/Universal_Credit_Local_Support_Services_Framework_-_CHC_Response,_March_2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://chcymru.org.uk/resources1/documents/key-issues/Universal_Credit_</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Local_Support_Services_Framework_-_CHC_Response,_March_2013.pdf</span></a></p></body></html>